  "prompt": "Is it generally understood that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is generally understood that money laundering is illegal. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This typically involves a series of transactions designed to obscure the origin of the funds, making it difficult for authorities to trace them back to illegal activities.\n\nLaws against money laundering are in place in many countries around the world, and these laws are designed to prevent criminals from profiting from their illegal activities. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and the seizure of assets.\n\nGiven the widespread recognition of its illegality and the serious consequences associated with it, money laundering is generally understood to be a crime.",
